'''Mikami clan''' (三上氏) was a historical {{ill|Japanese clan|ja|日本の氏族}}.

== Mikami clan of Mikami Shrine ==
{{日本の氏族 (古代氏族)
|氏名 = Mikami clan of Mikami Shrine
|image = 
|氏姓 = Mikami {{ill|Ason|ja|直}} ({{ill|Hōri|ja|祝}})
|始祖 = {{ill|Ame no Mikage no Kami|ja|天之御影神}}
|出自 = 
|氏祖 = Takihiko no Mikoto
|種別 = {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別}}
|本貫 = {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国}}{{ill|Yasu District, Ōmi Province|ja|野洲郡}}{{ill|Mikami|ja|三上郷}}{{Sfn|Ōta|1936|p=3745}}
|人物 = Mikami Kaeo
|後裔 = 
}}
The Mikami clan of Mikami Shrine was a group based in {{ill|Mikami|ja|三上郷}}, Yasu District, Ōmi Province. This clan served as the priestly lineage of {{ill|Mikami Shrine|ja|御上神社}}, historically tied to {{ill|Mount Mikami|ja|三上山}}.

Mikami Shrine claims the clan descends from {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神}}'s third son, {{ill|Amatsuhikone|ja|天津彦根命}}, and his descendant {{ill|Ame no Mikage no Kami|ja|天之御影神}}, who is said to have descended to Mount Mikami. 

According to {{ill|Mikami Shrine Historical Examination|ja|御上神社沿革考}}, Mount Mikami is believed to be the tomb of {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊弉諾命}} and {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命}}.{{Sfn|Ōtani|1899|p=3}}

== "Mikami" in ancient records ==
The term "Mikami" appears in several ancient texts. While some references pertain to people or places like Mikami District in {{ill|Bingo Province|ja|備後国}}, the connection to Ōmi Province is sparse. The most notable is a mention of "Mikami Shrine" in {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録}} in 865 (Jōgan 7) and 875 (Jōgan 17).{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992a|p=}}{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992b|p=}}{{Sfn|Morita|2006a|p=}}

== Mikami clan of Inaba Province ==
The Inaba Mikami clan, based in {{ill|Iwai District|ja|岩井庄}}, is believed to have been deputies sent by the {{ill|Yamana clan|ja|山名氏}} of Tajima Province. Their presence is documented from 1456 (Kōshō 2).{{Sfn|Takahashi|1986|p=}}

