The Mikami clan of Mikami Shrine was a group based in {{ill|Mikami|ja|三上郷|12=draft}}, Yasu District, Ōmi Province. This clan served as the priestly lineage of {{ill|Mikami Shrine|ja|御上神社|12=draft}}, historically tied to {{ill|Mount Mikami|ja|三上山|12=draft}}.

Mikami Shrine claims the clan descends from {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft}}'s third son, {{ill|Amatsuhikone|ja|天津彦根命|12=draft}}, and his descendant {{ill|Ame no Mikage no Kami|ja|天之御影神|12=draft}}, who is said to have descended to Mount Mikami. 

According to {{ill|Mikami Shrine Historical Examination|ja|御上神社沿革考|12=draft}}, Mount Mikami is believed to be the tomb of {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊弉諾命|12=draft}} and {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命|12=draft}}.{{Sfn|Ōtani|1899|p=3}}

== "Mikami" in ancient records ==
The term "Mikami" appears in several ancient texts. While some references pertain to people or places like Mikami District in {{ill|Bingo Province|ja|備後国|12=draft}}, the connection to Ōmi Province is sparse. The most notable is a mention of "Mikami Shrine" in {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft}} in 865 (Jōgan 7) and 875 (Jōgan 17).{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992a|p=}}{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992b|p=}}{{Sfn|Morita|2006a|p=}}

== Mikami clan of Inaba Province ==
The Inaba Mikami clan, based in {{ill|Iwai District|ja|岩井庄|12=draft}}, is believed to have been deputies sent by the {{ill|Yamana clan|ja|山名氏|12=draft}} of Tajima Province. Their presence is documented from 1456 (Kōshō 2).{{Sfn|Takahashi|1986|p=}}

