Mikami Shrine claims the clan descends from [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]]'s third son, {{ill|Amatsuhikone|ja|天津彦根命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amatsuhikone|qq=}}, and his descendant {{ill|Ame-no-Mikage-no-Kami|ja|天之御影神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame no Mikage no Kami|qq=}}, who is said to have descended to Mount Mikami. 

According to {{ill|Mikami Shrine Historical Examination|ja|御上神社沿革考|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikami Shrine Historical Examination|qq=}}, Mount Mikami is believed to be the tomb of {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊弉諾命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi|qq=}} and {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanami|qq=}}.{{Sfn|Ōtani|1899|p=3}}

== "Mikami" in ancient records ==
The term "Mikami" appears in several ancient texts. While some references pertain to people or places like Mikami District in [[:en:Bingo Province|Bingo Province]], the connection to Ōmi Province is sparse. The most notable is a mention of "Mikami Shrine" in [[:en:Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]] in 865 (Jōgan 7) and 875 (Jōgan 17).{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992a|p=}}{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992b|p=}}{{Sfn|Morita|2006a|p=}}

== Mikami clan of Inaba Province ==
The Inaba Mikami clan, based in {{ill|Iwai District|ja|岩井庄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwai District|qq=}}, is believed to have been deputies sent by the [[:en:Yamana clan|Yamana clan]] of Tajima Province. Their presence is documented from 1456 (Kōshō 2).{{Sfn|Takahashi|1986|p=}}

