According to {{ill|Mikami Shrine Historical Examination|ja|御上神社沿革考|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikami Shrine Historical Examination|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, Mount Mikami is believed to be the tomb of {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊弉諾命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to イザナギ}} and {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanami|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to イザナミ|1=Izanami|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q682306}}.{{Sfn|Ōtani|1899|p=3}}

== "Mikami" in ancient records ==
The term "Mikami" appears in several ancient texts. While some references pertain to people or places like Mikami District in {{ill|Bingo Province|en|Bingo Province|qid=Q1049113|lt=Bingo Province|1=Bingo Province}}, the connection to Ōmi Province is sparse. The most notable is a mention of "Mikami Shrine" in {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|en|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|qid=Q1052981|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}} in 865 (Jōgan 7) and 875 (Jōgan 17).{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992a|p=}}{{Sfn|Ujitani|1992b|p=}}{{Sfn|Morita|2006a|p=}}

== Mikami clan of Inaba Province ==
The Inaba Mikami clan, based in {{ill|Iwai District|ja|岩井庄|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwai District|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, is believed to have been deputies sent by the {{ill|Yamana clan|en|Yamana clan|qid=Q2975406|lt=Yamana clan|1=Yamana clan}} of Tajima Province. Their presence is documented from 1456 (Kōshō 2).{{Sfn|Takahashi|1986|p=}}

